sec.p:
The statutory model created in Amendment 28 was, in the words of Justice Beinisch, the President of the Court, the ‘improved English model’.8 This was shorthand for the fact that the powers of the operator and regime standards would be tightly regulated by the State. The defining characteristics included the following:


the State would select the successful bidder according to criteria that did not merely address price factors but included also regime quality factors;

the State would have comprehensive powers to approve, veto or remove staff;

the powers of the staff would be no greater, and in some respects would be less, than those of members of the Israeli Prison Service;

these powers included strip-searching in circumstances identical to those in which the Israeli Prison Service staff were entitled to carry out strip searches;

the areas where those powers were less extensive related particularly to the right of staff to use disciplinary procedures that would have the effect of increasing the effective length of a prisoner’s sentence;

the State would determine which prisoners would be sent to the prison and when and where they would be transferred to other prisons;

the State, acting through the Israeli Prison Service, would have untrammelled power to make unannounced or announced inspections of the prison operations or some particular aspect of those operations;

the contract to operate and manage the prison set out performance standards in precise detail;

the State would have an on-site monitoring presence to check contract compliance; and

the State retained the right to revoke the contract altogether for a wide range of performance deficiencies.
